{{Infobox artist | name = Adela Catherine Breton | image = Adela Breton.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth year|1849}} | birth_place = London, United Kingdom | death_date = {{Death year and age|1923|1849}} | death_place = Barbados | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | education = | field = [[Painting]], [[Archeology]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = | partner = }}
'''Adela Catherine Breton''' (31 December 1849 – June 1923) was an English [[archaeological]] artist and explorer. She made [[watercolour]] copies of the wall paintings of [[Mexico|Mexican]] temples, notably those of the Upper Temple of Jaguars at [[Chichen Itza]].
==Biography== Breton was born in [[London]] on 31 December 1849, to parents who were widely travelled. Her English father served in the [[Royal Navy]] and met Adela's mother (who was born in [[Somerset]], England) while in [[Tasmania]].<ref name=McVicker1234>McVicker, Chapter 1, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false pp 1–4]</ref> They moved to [[Bath, Somerset]], a few months after Adela's birth and she grew up there.<ref name=McVicker1234 /> During her childhood the family spent time travelling through Europe, visiting France, Switzerland and Italy. Adela probably studied art while staying in [[Florence]].<ref name=McVicker7to11>McVicker, Chapter 2, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false pp 7–11]</ref> With much of her time spent in Bath, with its Roman remains, the Bretons took a keen interest in the [[archaeology]].<ref name=McVicker7to11 /> She stayed in Bath to look after her parents in their old age but, after her father died in 1887, she decided to travel. She made a conscious decision not to marry, so she could remain independent and satisfy her wanderlust.<ref name=Bathexhib2016>{{cite news | url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/exhibition-celebrates-victorian-woman-left-bath/story-29194168-detail/story.html | title=Victorian woman who left Bath behind to document Maya ruins in Mexico is celebrated in exhibition | last=McFarlan | first=Tim | work=Bath Chronicle | date=28 April 2016 | access-date=1 May 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She initially headed for [[Canada]] (and the United States) where she painted the landscape, before returning to Bath to hold an exhibition of her paintings.<ref name=McVicker13to17>McVicker, Chapter 3, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false pp 13–17]</ref> In 1892 she made her first visit to Mexico. She hired a local guide, Pablo Solario.<ref name=McVicker13to17 />
Her time in Mexico was spent travelling on horseback across the country, using her artistic skills to record the friezes, carvings and other archaeological treasures that were being unearthed in the [[Yucatán]].<ref name=Bathexhib2016 /> Her first trip lasted 18 months, when she travelled continually making notes and sketches.<ref>McVicker, Chapter 4, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false pp 19–20]</ref> As the 1890s passed, Breton spent less time on return visits to England and more time on her travels in Mexico. Her observations became more scientific and broadened to include the geology, the canyons and volcanoes.<ref>McVicker, Chapter 6, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false pp 29–32]</ref> However, she is particularly known for her colour paintings of the frescos discovered at [[Teotihuacan]] in 1894, at a site that became known as [[Teopancaxco]].<ref>McVicker, Chapter 7, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false pp 33–36]</ref>
Breton's travels in Mexico were eventually curtailed by the [[Mexican revolution]] in 1910.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7TSs-hmJYYIC&pg=PA222#v=onepage&q&f=false McVicker, ''Adela Breton: A Victorian Artist Amid Mexico's Ruins'', back page]</ref> She was recognised internationally in her lifetime for her valuable contribution to Mesoamerican archaeology.<ref name=Bathexhib2016 />
She died in [[Barbados]] in 1923 age 73.<ref name=Bathexhib2016 />
==Legacy== [[File:Breton Maya Mural Chichen Itza.jpg | thumb | Watercolour by Adele Breton of one of the murals at Chichén Itzá.]]A collection of her work is held in [[Bristol Museum & Art Gallery]], where a [[digitisation]] project was started in 2014 so that the fragile rolls of paintings can be preserved and made available for research.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Giles|first1=Sue|last2=Harland|first2=Valerie|title=Digitisation of the Adela Breton collection at Bristol Museum & Art Gallery|url=https://www.artuk.org/discover/stories/digitisation-of-the-adela-breton-collection-at-bristol-museum-art-gallery|publisher=[[Art UK|Public Catalogue Foundation]]|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=13 November 2014}}</ref>
Some of her correspondence with Ella Lewis of [[Philadelphia]] is held in [[Harvard University Library]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Breton, Adela, (1849-1923), Correspondence, 1915-1923, bulk: A Finding Aid|url=http://oasis.lib.harvard.edu/oasis/deliver/~pea00053|publisher=Harvard University Library|accessdate=18 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002213400/http://oasis.lib.harvard.edu/oasis/deliver/~pea00053|archive-date=2014-10-02|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
In 2016 a four-month exhibition entitled "The Remarkable Miss Breton" was held at the Bath Royal Literary & Scientific Institution in Bath.<ref name=Bathexhib2016 /> In 2017 an exhibition of her original work was held at the Bristol Museum & Art Gallery.
